# Architecture Decision Records (ADRs)

This folder captures the **why** behind every non-obvious technical decision in this project. Each file documents one decision: the problem we faced, what we chose, what we considered and rejected, and how the choice connects to the long-term plan in [`../../ROADMAP.md`](../../ROADMAP.md).

## When to write an ADR

Write a new ADR whenever a decision is made that:

- Has more than one reasonable answer.
- Will be costly or confusing to revisit later if the reasoning isn't recorded.
- Affects how future contributors (including AI sessions) write code.

Routine choices that are obvious from the code itself (variable names, internal helper structure, etc.) don't need ADRs.

## Format

Each ADR follows the template in [`template.md`](./template.md). Required sections:

| Section | What it captures |
|---|---|
| **Status** | `accepted` / `superseded by ADR-NNNN` / `deprecated` |
| **Date** | When the decision was first made |
| **Context** | The problem we were solving |
| **Decision** | What we chose |
| **Alternatives considered** | What we rejected, and why |
| **Consequences** | Tradeoffs we accepted; constraints this places on future work |
| **Roadmap alignment** | Which roadmap phase / strategic decision (D1..DN) this serves |

## Lifecycle

ADRs are **immutable once accepted**. If a decision later changes:

1. Create a new ADR documenting the new decision.
2. Update the old ADR's `Status` to `superseded by ADR-NNNN` (link to the new one).
3. Don't edit the body of the superseded ADR — the historical reasoning is the point.

